Motivation and Background¶

Give an overview of the project, motivation, background and goals.

Fireworks are a class of low explosive pyrotechnic devices used for aesthetic and entertainment purposes, commonly as part of a fireworks display/pyrotechnics. Fireworks are often bought during celebrations all around the world. However, fireworks can also cause injuries and fires. I would like to analyze the trend of the popularity of fireworks, as well as whether or not COVID-19 has affected this demand, as well as the frequency of injuries over the years.

Summary of Research Questions & Results¶

Repeat your research questions in a numbered list. After each research question, clearly state the answer/conclusion you determined. Do not give details or justifications yet — just the answer

  1. Has the popularity of fireworks increased or decreased over time? Increased

  2. When in the year are fireworks most popular? 4th of July, Deepavali, New Years Day

    • When in the year are firework injuries most common?

  3. Has the rate of fireworks injuries increased or decreased over time? Not statistically significant

  4. Breaking down Fireworks-Related Injuries
    • by Age
    • by Sex
    • by Race
    • by Body Part injured
  5. Has the pandemic affected sales of fireworks and injury rate of fireworks as professional events were cancelled?

  6. https://dataweb.usitc.gov/ This is the portal for accessing USA imports and exports of goods. I made an account and made the following request:

    • Step 1: Trade Flow and Classification System

      • Trade Flow : Imports For Consumption
      • Classification System HTS Items

    • Step 2: Data and Years

      • Data To Report : Customs Value, First Unit of Quantity, Second Unit of Quantity
      • Data Format : 1
      • Years 1989-2022
      • Timeframe Aggregation Annual

    • Step 3: Countries

      • Select Type : Use All Countries
      • Country Aggregation : Aggregate countries

    • Step 4: Commodities

      • Select Type : Select Individual Commodities
      • Commodity List : 360410
      • Commodity Aggregation : Level 6
      • Commodity Aggregation : Aggregate Commodities
      • Description Display : NO

    • Step 5: Programs

      • Select Type : Use All Programs
      • Import Program Aggregation : Aggregate CSC

    • Step 6: Rate Provision Codes

      • Select Type : Use All Provision Codes
      • Provision Code Aggregation : Aggregate RPCODE

    • Step 7: Districts

      • Select Type : Use All Districts
      • District Aggregation : Aggregate District

    • Step 8: Report Layout

      • Column Order : UNITS
      • Percent Change Column : Unchecked
      • Show All : Checked
      • Enable Subtotals : Unchecked

  7. https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?q=firework Google Trends data for fireworks

  8. CPSC (U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission)'s annual fireworks report. Estimated Injuries were parsed from their tables for years 2003, 2019 and 2021.

Source 3 - USA population over time¶

one thing that I have learnt from this, it is that standards, file types, etc change with time, so there will not be much purpose doing this fully automatically especially when there's a new data format in the next 10-20 years.

We first combine 2000-2021 data for total, race, age and sex

In [3]:
age_cols = ["Under 5","5-9","10-14","15-19","20-24","25-29","30-34","35-39",'40-44','45-49','50-54','55-59','60-64','65-69','70-74','75-79','80-84','85 and over']
age_cols_2000 = age_cols[:-1] + ['85-89','90-94','95-99','100 and over']
sex_cols = ['male','female']
race_cols = ['White','Black','AIAN','Asian','NHPI','Two or More Races']

# 2000-2009
us_pop_2000 = pd.read_csv("us_pop_2000-2009.csv").replace({',':''},regex=True)
t2000_2009 = us_pop_2000[3:25]
us_sex_2000 = us_pop_2000.iloc[[42,81]]

t2000_2009 = pd.concat([t2000_2009,us_sex_2000])

t2000_2009.columns = range(1998,2012)
t2000_2009 = t2000_2009[range(2000,2010)]
t2000_2009 = t2000_2009.T.apply(pd.to_numeric)
t2000_2009.columns = ["total"] + age_cols_2000 + sex_cols
t2000_2009["85 and over"] = t2000_2009['85-89'] + t2000_2009['90-94'] + t2000_2009['95-99'] + t2000_2009['100 and over']
t2000_2009 = t2000_2009[['total'] + age_cols + sex_cols]

us_pop_2000_r = pd.read_csv("us_pop_2000-2009_by_race.csv")[3:].replace({',':''},regex=True)
us_pop_2000_r.columns = range(1998,2012)
us_pop_2000_r = us_pop_2000_r[range(2000,2010)].iloc[2:8].T.apply(pd.to_numeric)
us_pop_2000_r.columns = race_cols
t2000_2009 = t2000_2009.merge(us_pop_2000_r, left_index=True, right_index=True)

# 2010-2019
us_pop_2010 = pd.read_excel('us_pop_2010-2019.xlsx', engine='openpyxl')[4:]
t2010_2019 = us_pop_2010[:19]
us_sex_2010 = us_pop_2010.iloc[[36,72]]

t2010_2019 = pd.concat([t2010_2019,us_sex_2010])

t2010_2019.columns = range(2007,2020)
t2010_2019 = t2010_2019[range(2010,2020)].T
t2010_2019.columns = ['total'] + age_cols + sex_cols


for race in race_cols:
    us_pop_2010_r = pd.read_excel('us_pop_2010-2019.xlsx', engine='openpyxl', sheet_name=race).iloc[[4]]
    us_pop_2010_r.columns = range(2007,2020)
    us_pop_2010_r = us_pop_2010_r[range(2010,2020)].T
    us_pop_2010_r.columns = [race]
    t2010_2019 = t2010_2019.merge(us_pop_2010_r, left_index=True, right_index=True)

# 2020-2021
us_pop_2020 = pd.read_excel('us_pop_2020-2021.xlsx', engine='openpyxl')[3:]
t2020_2021 = us_pop_2020[:19]
us_sex_2020 = us_pop_2020.iloc[[36,72]]

t2020_2021 = pd.concat([t2020_2021, us_sex_2020])

t2020_2021.columns = range(2018,2022)
t2020_2021 = t2020_2021[range(2020,2022)].T
t2020_2021.columns = ['total'] + age_cols + sex_cols

for race in race_cols:
    us_pop_2020_r = pd.read_excel('us_pop_2020-2021.xlsx', engine='openpyxl', sheet_name=race).iloc[[4]]
    us_pop_2020_r.columns = range(2018,2022)
    us_pop_2020_r = us_pop_2020_r[range(2020,2022)].T
    us_pop_2020_r.columns = [race]
    t2020_2021 = t2020_2021.merge(us_pop_2020_r, left_index=True, right_index=True)

t2000_2021 = pd.concat([t2000_2009, t2010_2019, t2020_2021]).astype(int)

Data Cleaning¶

For data cleaning, be clear in which dataset (or variables) are used, what has been done for missing data, how was merging performed, explanation of data transformation (if any). If data is calculated or summarized from the raw dataset, explain the rationale and steps clearly.

Cleaning NEISS Injury sampling data

Many of the original csvs had random newlines inserted into the data, those were found with some code and were manually removed

We first preliminarily filter reports to those that only include 'FIREWORK' and 'FIRE WORK', or those which have a Product ID have 1313 (Fireworks)

In [13]:
# filter NEISS data for only fireworks
dtypes = {
        "CPSC_Case_Number": "Int64",
        "Age": "Int64",
        "Sex": "Int64",
        "Race": "Int64",
        "Other_Race": "string",
        "Hispanic": "Int64",
        "Body_Part": "Int64",
        "Diagnosis": "Int64",
        "Other_Diagnosis": "string",
        "Body_Part_2": "Int64",
        "Diagnosis_2": "Int64",
        "Other_Diagnosis_2": "string",
        "Disposition": "Int64",  
        "Location": "Int64",
        "Fire_Involvement": "Int64",
        "Product_1": "Int64",
        "Product_2": "Int64",
        "Product_3": "Int64",
        "Alcohol": "Int64",
        "Drug": "Int64",
        "Narrative": "string",
        "Stratum": "string",
        "PSU": "Int64",
        "Weight": "float64"
}
NEISS_df = None
start = 2002
end = 2021
for i in range(start,end+1):
    print(f'opening {i}')
    df = pd.read_csv(f'neiss{i}.tsv', sep='\t', dtype=dtypes, parse_dates=["Treatment_Date"])
    if i>=2020:
        df = df.rename(columns={"Narrative_1":"Narrative"})
    # choose all fireworks
    df = df.loc[(df.Narrative.str.count('FIREWORK')>0) | (df.Narrative.str.count('FIRE WORK')>0) | (df.Product_1==1313) | (df.Product_2==1313) | (df.Product_3==1313)].copy()
    # remove all firecrackers
    df = df.loc[(df.Narrative.str.count('FIRE CRACK')==0) & (df.Narrative.str.count('FIRECRACK')==0)]
    df.loc[:, "year"] = i
    if i == start:
        NEISS_df = df
    else:
        NEISS_df = pd.concat([NEISS_df, df])
NEISS_df = NEISS_df.reset_index(drop=True)

# for future storage so that this massive codeblock doesnt have to run everytime:
NEISS_df.to_csv('neiss.csv')

Cleaning Google Trends data¶

In [15]:
google_trends = None
for i in range(2004,2022):
    df = pd.read_csv(f"firework{i}.csv")
    df = df.reset_index()
    df.columns = ["week", "firework"]
    df = df[1:]
    if i == 2004:
        google_trends = df
    else:
        google_trends = pd.concat([google_trends, df])
google_trends.week = pd.to_datetime(google_trends.week)
google_trends.firework = pd.to_numeric(google_trends.firework)
google_trends.columns = ["date", "firework"]

Question 1: Are Fireworks getting more popular?¶

We have a variety of sources that we can use to determine the popularity of the fireworks over the years. These are:

  1. [1989-2021] Fireworks revenue (USA)
  2. [2002-2021] Imports (Worldwide)
  3. [1989-2021] Imports (USA, different source from 2. with different values likely due to different between "Value" and "Customs Value")
  4. [2004-2021] Google Trends (Worldwide)

In order to compare the trends of all these datasets with each other, the data is normalized it relative to 2004 (i.e. set year 2004 as 1, and all values other values are its original value relative to the 2004 data value). This is to reconcile the wildly different data values used to measure "popularity"

Then we can plot all of them and see the trend. Due to the large number of metrics, we use small multiples

In [16]:
# fireworks revenue (USA)
revenue_2004 = revenue[revenue.year==2004]
norm_rev = revenue.copy()
norm_rev["display fireworks revenue"] = revenue["display fireworks revenue"]/revenue_2004["display fireworks revenue"].iloc[0]
norm_rev["consumer fireworks revenue"] = revenue["consumer fireworks revenue"]/revenue_2004["consumer fireworks revenue"].iloc[0]

# worldwide imports
i_2004 = firework_imports[firework_imports.year==2004].World.iloc[0]
norm_import = firework_imports[["year", "World"]].copy()
norm_import.World = norm_import.World/i_2004
# worldwide exports
e_2004 = firework_exports[firework_exports.year==2004].World.iloc[0]
norm_export = firework_exports[["year", "World"]].copy()
norm_export.World = norm_export.World/e_2004
# merge the worldwides
norm_world = norm_import.merge(norm_export, how='outer', on='year')
norm_world.columns = ['year', 'world imports', 'world exports']

# USA imports
usa_2004 = imports_usa[imports_usa.year==2004]["Customs Value"].iloc[0]
norm_usa = imports_usa.copy()
norm_usa["Customs Value"] = norm_usa["Customs Value"]/usa_2004

usa_kg_2004 = imports_usa_kg[imports_usa_kg.year==2004]["weight"].iloc[0]
norm_usa_kg = imports_usa_kg.copy()
norm_usa_kg["weight"] = norm_usa_kg["weight"]/usa_kg_2004

norm_us = norm_usa.merge(norm_usa_kg, on='year', how='outer')

# Google Trends
google_trends_yr = google_trends.groupby(google_trends.date.dt.year)[["firework"]].sum() # groupby year
google_trends_yr.firework = google_trends_yr.firework/google_trends_yr.firework.loc[2004]
google_trends_yr = google_trends_yr.reset_index()
google_trends_yr.columns = ['year','google trends firework']

nrow = 2
ncol = 2
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))
gs = fig.add_gridspec(nrow, ncol, hspace=0.2, wspace=0)

We can see that across multiple metrics the popularity of fireworks over time has been slowly but consistently increasing, with the notable exception of Google Trends. We also see that in terms of revenue, the COVID years caused a spike in revenue for consumer fireworks and a dip for display fireworks, which will be further investigated in Question 4.

Question 2: When in the year are fireworks popular?¶

For this question we can only use the Google Trends data, which sorts data by the week

We then make a heatmap with week against year, seeing which weeks are the most popular for fireworks.

Note that the "weeks" represents how many multiples of 7s there are since the start of the year, rather than the more convential week based on Sunday

In [17]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
gt = google_trends.copy()
gt["year"] = gt["date"].dt.year
gt["week"] = (gt["date"].dt.dayofyear - 1) // 7 + 1
gt_pivot = gt.pivot(index='year', columns='week', values='firework') 
heatmap = sns.heatmap(gt_pivot, cmap="magma")
heatmap.set_xlabel("week no.")
plt.show()

We can see that fireworks are very popular around weeks 25 - 27, which correspond to the 4th of July celebration in the United States.

We also see that fireworks experience another surge in popularity in week 43 and 44, likley corresponding to Deepavali, or Thanksgiving.

It is harder to see this, but near the end of the heatmap, on the last week of the year, fireworks experiences yet another surge in popularity due to the New Year Celebrations.

Less relevant to the findings, but we can see that the unusual activity from late 2010 to 2011 was caused by the song "Firework" being released by Katy Perry.

We can also plot a heatmap for injuries as those should correlate with real firework usage (in the USA):

Question 3: Has the rate of fireworks injuries increased or decreased over time?¶

Currently I only have data for the USA so this question is really more "Has the rate of firework injuries increased or decreased over time in America"

I have two sources, the annual fireworks report which estimates the true value and the direct NEISS data, which is a sample of the data available

I did a similar thing in Q1 where I normalized them at year 2002 and see the overall trend from the year 2002

In [21]:
NEISS_injuries_by_year = NEISS_df.groupby('year')[['CPSC_Case_Number']].count().reset_index(drop=False).rename(columns={'CPSC_Case_Number':'Number of Injuries'})

However this does not take into account population increase. Let's take that into account:

In [22]:
# use NEISS counts
us_population = t1980_2021[t1980_2021.year>2001].reset_index(drop=True).us_population

NEISS_injuries_by_year['Injury rate'] = NEISS_injuries_by_year['Injury rate']/norm_const

est_injuries = firework_estimated_injuries.copy()

It does not seem like a clear trend. We do not include the covid years (2020-2021) as that will be investigated in a later question. We can find out if this trend is statistically significant or not:

In [23]:
est_injuries_pre_covid = firework_estimated_injuries[firework_estimated_injuries.Year<2020]
pearson_coef, p_value = stats.pearsonr(est_injuries_pre_covid['Year'], est_injuries_pre_covid['Estimated Injuries'])
print(f"CPSC estimates: R²: {pearson_coef**2}, p-value: {p_value}")

neiss_injuries_pre_covid = NEISS_injuries_by_year[NEISS_injuries_by_year.year<2020]
pearson_coef, p_value = stats.pearsonr(neiss_injuries_pre_covid['year'], neiss_injuries_pre_covid['Injury rate'])
print(f"NEISS injuries: R²: {pearson_coef**2}, p-value: {p_value}")

CPSC estimates: R²: 0.0007937147867804917, p-value: 0.8846549039632713
NEISS injuries: R²: 0.019112301950937594, p-value: 0.584334810683719

Since R²<0.65 and p-value>=0.05 for both, the trend of increase (or any trend for that matter) is not statistically significant, so we can conclude that firework injuries have not increased or decreased in any way (pre-covid)

def categorize_body_part(x):
    if(x in [30, 33, 80, 94]):
        return "Arm/Shoulder"
    if(x in [77]):
        return "Eye"
    if(x in [34, 82, 92]):
        return "Hand/Finger"
    if(x in [32, 75, 76, 88]):
        return "Head/Face/Ear"
    if(x in [35, 36, 37, 81, 83, 93]):
        return "Leg"
    if(x in [31, 38, 79, 89]):
        return "Trunk"
    return "Other"
body_parts["body_region"] = body_parts.Body_Part.apply(categorize_body_part)
body_parts = body_parts.groupby("body_region")["count"].sum()
body_parts = body_parts.sort_values(ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))
plt.pie(
    body_parts,
    shadow=False,
    colors=['#1F77B4', '#FF7F0E', "#2CA02C", "#D62728", "#9467BD", "#8C564B", "Pink"],
    startangle=0,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    labels=body_parts.index
)
plt.show()

We see that Hand/Fingers are the most common type of injury, followed by those to the eye, then those to the Head/Face/Ear.

Question 4: Has the pandemic affected sales of fireworks and injury rate of fireworks as professional events were cancelled?¶

Lets first investigate the injury rate of fireworks.

In [34]:
neiss_injury_rate = neiss_injuries_pre_covid["Injury rate"]
mean, var  = stats.distributions.norm.fit(neiss_injury_rate)

fitted_neiss_injury_rate = stats.distributions.norm.pdf(x, mean, var)

In [35]:
covid_neiss_injury_rate = NEISS_injuries_by_year[NEISS_injuries_by_year.year == 2020]["Injury rate"].iloc[0]
stats.distributions.norm.pdf(covid_neiss_injury_rate, mean, var)
Out[35]:
6.853711661250975e-06

This means that there is a 0.00069% chance that, at random, a year will have an injury rate greater than or equal to the COVID year's injury rate (from NEISS data). This is far below the 5% threshold so we can say with certainty that COVID has increased the injury rate significantly.

Next let's investigate the revenue. However since the revenue has an increasing trend, we first have to make a linear regression model. Starting with fireworks revenue in the US:

In [36]:
lm = LinearRegression()
revenue_precovid = revenue[revenue.year<2020]
ŷ = lm.fit(revenue_precovid[["year"]], revenue_precovid["display fireworks revenue"])
ŷ = lm.predict(revenue[['year']])
e = revenue['display fireworks revenue'] - ŷ # residue
plt.plot(revenue.year, e, 'o')
plt.plot([1998,2021], [0,0], color="red")
plt.ylabel("residue of display fireworks revenue")

lm = LinearRegression()

As we can see, that is a huge decrease in display fireworks revenue in 2020 and 2021, especialy 2020. The opposite is true for consumer fireworks revenue - it skyrocketed up in 2020, and further increased in 2021.

neiss_date_log = np.log(neiss_date_pivot+1)
plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))

heatmap.set_xlabel("day of year")
plt.title("Fourth of July, New Year is the main time fireworks are used (and cause injuries)")
plt.show()

It is blindingly obvious that there is a huge spike of firework-related injuries (and hence firework popularity) during the 4th of July. We can see that there is another peak at the ends - which corresponds to the new year's celebration, although it is still behind the 4th of july in terms of injuries (and hence popularity).

We can also see from the logarithmic heatmap that injuries are more common leading up to and after the fourth of july celebrations, as compared to the rest of the year.

Question 4 (iv): Breaking down Fireworks-Related Injuries by Body Part¶

we first divide the body parts it into several categories:

  1. Arm/Shoulder
  2. Eye
  3. Hand/Finger
  4. Head/Face/Ear
  5. Leg
  6. Trunk
  7. Others

We can then analyze it by body region

In [52]:
body_parts = NEISS_df[NEISS_df.Body_Part!=87] # remove entries that are not recorded
body_parts = NEISS_df.groupby('Body_Part')[['CPSC_Case_Number']].count()
body_parts.columns = ['count']
body_parts = body_parts.reset_index().sort_values(by='count',ascending=False)

def categorize_body_part(x):
    if(x in [30, 33, 80, 94]):
        return "Arm/Shoulder"
    if(x in [77]):
        return "Eye"
    if(x in [34, 82, 92]):
        return "Hand/Finger"
    if(x in [32, 75, 76, 88]):
        return "Head/Face/Ear"
    if(x in [35, 36, 37, 81, 83, 93]):
        return "Leg"
    if(x in [31, 38, 79, 89]):
        return "Trunk"
    return "Other"
body_parts["body_region"] = body_parts.Body_Part.apply(categorize_body_part)
body_parts = body_parts.groupby("body_region")["count"].sum()
body_parts = body_parts.sort_values(ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))
plt.pie(
    body_parts,
    shadow=False,
    colors=['#1F77B4', '#FF7F0E', "#2CA02C", "#D62728", "#9467BD", "#8C564B", "Pink"],
    startangle=0,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    labels=body_parts.index
)
plt.show()

We see that Hand/Fingers are the most common type of injury, followed by those to the eye, then those to the Head/Face/Ear. about 1/3 of all firework related injuries are those to the hand/finger, which makes sense especially since when a firework is mishandled or malfunctioning, the patient was probably holding it in his hand or touching it. The large Eye sector could be a bias - not all hand injuries need or necessitate hospital care; but eye injuries almost always necessitate a visit. A similar situation could be ongoing for the the Head/Face/Ear category.

In blue is the kernel density estimation of the NEISS Injury rate dataset pre-covid, in red is the fitted normal distribution, and in orange the point is the 2020 injury rate. There is a 0.00069% chance that such an increase in injury rate will occur naturally, so we can conclude the The pandemic has caused injury rates to increase.

As we can see, that is a huge decrease in display fireworks revenue in 2020 and 2021, especialy 2020. The opposite is true for consumer fireworks revenue - it skyrocketed up in 2020, and further increased in 2021. Hence we can conclude that COVID 19 has affected the revenue of fieworks.

Recommendations or Further Works

State any recommendations, improvements or further works.

On Firework Injuries¶

I would recommend parents/guardians with children to take special care when using fireworks around children, or letting children view fireworks, as from the data, young children and tweens have the highest injury rate from fireworks.

Since fireworks, especially consumer fireworks are only really used on special occasions, depending on the cultures, extra care must be taken during those times to prevent injuries from occuring, and be wary of injuries to the eye.

Generally, display fireworks are less dangerous than self-lit fireworks so more care has to be taken for self-lit fireworks aka consumer fireworks.

Further Works¶

There are many biases in this report, because a lot of the analysis relies on one data source, and hospital cases do not necessarily reflect injury rates. In addition, an analysis by firework device type would also be useful to know which fireworks are more dangerous than others.
